{"analysis": "The query groups orders by whether a discount campaign was active and computes the average order value (AOV) for each group. On non-campaign days, AOV is 12,616.93 across 1,834 orders, while on campaign days AOV drops to 9,693.25 across 484 orders. This represents a difference of approximately 2,923.68, or roughly 23% lower AOV on campaign days compared to non-campaign days.

The direction of the effect is consistent with the hypothesis: campaign days show a lower average order value than non-campaign days. The sample sizes (1,834 vs 484) are reasonably large, which lends descriptive weight to the observed gap — a ~23% difference across hundreds-to-thousands of orders is unlikely to be purely noise, and the magnitude is economically meaningful.

Caveats worth noting: (1) this is a simple group-by without a formal significance test, confidence interval, or variance estimate, so we cannot rigorously quantify uncertainty from this output alone; (2) 'lower AOV on campaign days' is expected almost by construction if campaigns apply discounts to the order total, so the result confirms the hypothesis as stated but does not distinguish between a pure discount-mechanical effect and a behavioral effect (e.g., customers buying more units but at lower per-order totals); (3) confounding by seasonality, product mix, or customer segment is not controlled for. Nevertheless, the hypothesis as literally stated — that AOV on campaign days is lower than on non-campaign days — is directly supported by the descriptive statistics.", "verdict": "supported", "evidence_summary": "Campaign-day AOV (9,693.25) is approximately 23% lower than non-campaign-day AOV (12,616.93) across 484 vs 1,834 orders, directly supporting the hypothesis."}
